// ============================================================================
// cleanroom_stress_part6.jai
//
// Sixth giant block of reference compatibility tests. Loaded via #load from
// the main file. Exports run_extras_6(). Deterministic output: ASCII only, no
// addresses, no paths, no timing, no OS-specific values. Pointers are
// reported as nullity ("non-null"/"null") only.
//
// Topic coverage (high level):
//
//   600 series : Reflection sweep over primitives, arrays, structs, enums,
//                polymorphic structs, and a deeply nested struct.
//   601 series : Manual struct serializer that emits a string representation
//                of any struct via type_info introspection.
//   602 series : Manual binary blob writer/reader (memcpy round trip).
//   603 series : Field walker counting integer/float/string/struct/pointer
//                fields for a variety of structs.
//   604 series : Enum operations: many enum types, names, values, range,
//                #specified bit, bitwise enum_flags ops, flag combo
//                decomposition.
//   605 series : Polymorphic structs galore (PE6_Box/Pair/Triple/Quad/Map/Stack/
//                Queue/Ring/Fixed_List).
//   606 series : Polymorphic procedure forms (variadic-with-polymorph,
//                $T-with-bake, named return, $$T compile-time-only constant,
//                #if T == ... else).
//   607 series : Generic print_pretty over Any with reflection.
//   608 series : Generic recursive equals over Any.
//   609 series : Tiny stack-machine interpreter (PUSH/POP/ADD/SUB/MUL/DIV/
//                PRINT) plus a small program.
//   610 series : Ackermann on small inputs.
//   611 series : Iterate every Type_Info_Tag variant.
//   612 series : Varint integer compression (encode and decode round trip).
//   613 series : Base64-like alphabet encoder built from scratch.
//   614 series : Hex encode / decode of byte arrays.
//   615 series : LRU cache over a fixed-size circular buffer.
//
// Conventions:
//   * No #place. No <<. No I/O. No time. No OS lookups.
//   * Output is fully deterministic.
//   * Helpers section(...) and sub(...) are defined in the main file.
//   * Each "test" produces strictly labelled output.
// ============================================================================


// ============================================================================
// Local helper type definitions used by many sections below.
// ============================================================================

